{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014h8JazW4EFPPpfxjFKo2eM","type":"tool_result","content":"0\t---\n1\tstepsCompleted: ['step-01-init', 'step-02-discovery', 'step-02b-vision', 'step-02c-executive-summary', 'step-03-success', 'step-04-journeys', 'step-05-domain', 'step-06-innovation', 'step-07-project-type', 'step-08-scoping', 'step-09-functional', 'step-10-nonfunctional', 'step-11-polish', 'step-12-complete']\n2\tinputDocuments:\n3\t  - research/domain-harness-design-long-running-agents-research-2026-04-01.md\n4\t  - research/technical-ai-agent-verification-testing-research-2026-03-16.md\n5\t  - research/technical-workflow-engine-implementation-research-2026-04-02.md\n6\t  - product-brief-bmad-orchestrator-2026-03-14.md\n7\t  - prd.md (existing completed PRD, used as brownfield context)\n8\tdocumentCounts:\n9\t  briefs: 1\n10\t  research: 3\n11\t  brainstorming: 0\n12\t  projectDocs: 1\n13\tworkflowType: 'prd'\n14\tclassification:\n15\t  projectType: developer_tool\n16\t  domain: general\n17\t  complexity: high\n18\t  projectContext: brownfield\n19\t  designPhilosophy: declarative-first\n20\t---\n21\t\n22\t# Product Requirements Document - codeharness v2\n23\t\n24\t**Author:** BMad\n25\t**Date:** 2026-04-01 (updated 2026-04-02, edited 2026-04-02)\n26\t\n27\t## Executive Summary\n28\t\n29\tcodeharness is an npm CLI and Claude Code plugin that makes autonomous coding agents produce software that actually works. Version 1 proved the concept — Ralph loop, BMAD integration, observability stack, verification hooks. But the verification architecture is fundamentally broken: the agent that writes the code also grades it. Anthropic's own research confirms this fails — \"models praise their own work confidently even when quality is mediocre.\"\n30\t\n31\tThis redesign replaces the current hardcoded execution loop and self-verification theater with three things:\n32\t\n33\t1. **A declarative workflow engine** that drives multi-agent execution. A YAML workflow definition specifies task states, transitions, per-task prompts, agent assignments, expected inputs/outputs, and session boundaries (fresh context vs. continuation). This replaces Ralph's 1000+ lines of bash orchestration with something configurable and clean. Execution uses the Claude Agent SDK (`@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`) — the official TypeScript API for programmatic Claude Code control.\n34\t\n35\t2. **A single adversarial verification pass** against the final built artifact. No per-story micro-verification. No session flags. No proof document regex parsing. One blind evaluator agent — no source code access, only Docker, observability, and documentation — exercises the final artifact subjectively and produces a structured JSON verdict. The evaluator reads ACs in user language and independently figures out how to test them.\n36\t\n37\t3. **A multi-level agent and workflow configuration system.** Agents and workflows exist at three levels: embedded (ships with codeharness), user-level, and project-level — with hybrid patching to customize without replacing. 9 embedded agents (8 BMAD + evaluator) and 1 default workflow ship out of the box. Agent personality uses BMAD-compatible fields as the base with optional PersonaNexus-compatible traits for fine-grained behavioral tuning.\n38\t\n39\tBMAD owns planning (briefs, PRDs, architecture, stories). Codeharness owns execution and verification — taking BMAD's output and driving it to a proven-working artifact.\n40\t\n41\t### What Makes This Special\n42\t\n43\t- **Declarative, not imperative.** Workflow YAML defines agent dispatch, session control, and handoff contracts. No more reading bash to understand what happens next.\n44\t- **Honest verification.** One blind evaluator at the end, exercising the real artifact subjectively. The verifier can't see source, can't be fooled by passing tests, can't talk itself into approval. Structured JSON evidence required for every AC verdict.\n45\t- **Configurable everything.** Agents and workflows are configurable at embedded, user, and project levels. Patch any embedded agent or workflow without replacing it — override specific fields or append to prompts.\n46\t- **Agent-as-assignee with structured personality.** Tasks are assigned to specific agents with BMAD personas and optional quantified personality traits (warmth, rigor, directness, etc.). The evaluator is tuned for high rigor and zero leniency.\n47\t- **Aggressive legacy removal.** The 4-format proof parser, session flags, self-verification path, per-story hooks, and hardcoded Ralph logic all get deleted. Only clean code survives.\n48\t\n49\t### Project Classification\n50\t\n51\t- **Type:** Developer tool (CLI + Claude Code plugin)\n52\t- **Domain:** General software engineering tooling\n53\t- **Complexity:** High — workflow engine, multi-agent orchestration, session isolation, agent configuration system, observability integration, major legacy rework\n54\t- **Context:** Brownfield — significant architectural rework of working system\n55\t- **Design Philosophy:** Declarative-first — YAML workflows and agent configs drive behavior\n56\t\n57\t## Success Criteria\n58\t\n59\t### User Success\n60\t\n61\t- User runs `codeharness run` with the default workflow — all stories execute through assigned agents without human intervention\n62\t- The blind evaluator exercises the final artifact and produces a pass/fail verdict the user trusts\n63\t- Workflow YAML is understandable in under 5 minutes\n64\t- When the evaluator rejects, the feedback is specific enough that the user (or agent on retry) knows exactly what to fix\n65\t- User can customize agent behavior and workflows via patches without editing codeharness source\n66\t\n67\t### Business Success\n68\t\n69\t- Personal/OSS developer tool — adoption metrics are secondary to the tool actually working\n70\t- Success = the author uses it to ship real projects autonomously with confidence in the output\n71\t\n72\t### Technical Success\n73\t\n74\t- **Lines of code reduction.** Net negative LOC count after the rework\n75\t- **Test coverage.** Unit test coverage for `src/lib/` rises from ~5% to 80%+\n76\t- **Workflow YAML is the single source of truth** for execution behavior\n77\t- **One verification path.** Blind evaluator session or nothing\n78\t\n79\t### Measurable Outcomes\n80\t\n81\t| Metric | Current | Target |\n82\t|--------|---------|--------|\n83\t| Source LOC (src/) | Measure at start | Net reduction |\n84\t| Unit test coverage (src/lib/) | ~5% | 80%+ |\n85\t| Verification code paths | 4+ | 1 (blind evaluator) |\n86\t| Ralph bash LOC | ~1000 | 0 (replaced by workflow engine) |\n87\t| Workflow definition format | Hardcoded in ralph-prompt.ts | YAML file |\n88\t\n89\t## Product Scope\n90\t\n91\t### MVP (Phase 1)\n92\t\n93\t**MVP Approach:** Problem-solving — replace broken self-verification with adversarial evaluation. Success = \"does it catch bugs that v1 missed?\"\n94\t\n95\t**Resource:** Solo developer + autonomous agents (codeharness eating its own dogfood).\n96\t\n97\t**Must-Have Capabilities:**\n98\t1. Workflow YAML parser with JSON schema validation\n99\t2. Flow execution engine (sequential steps, `loop:` blocks, task scope resolution)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0155ShxPeo4aZZxJMe6PsZMC","session_id":"82c789c3-0c3c-4e9f-a910-db433860b9ed","uuid":"835e372d-9009-4218-8e19-7c8fbdc291ca","timestamp":"2026-04-02T15:54:01.504Z"}
